Cyclistic bike-share
analysis case study
Benjino Chery
Intro
Bicycle commuting has emerged as a compelling and sustainable
solution to the transportation challenges of modern life; especially in
big cities where traffic congestion, environmental concerns, and
health considerations converge.
As a leading bike-share company, Cyclistic offers an eco-friendly and
efficient mode of transportation to Chicagoans and visitors alike. This
case study delves into the heart of Cyclistic's mission, illuminating
how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistics bikes
differently to develop a marketing strategy that maximizes the
annual membership conversions.
Problem
Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day
passes are referred to as casual riders. Customers
who purchase annual memberships are Cyclistic
members.
How casual riders and annual
members use Cyclistic bikes
differently?

Summary
Ride Patterns:
• Casual users tend to have longer ride lengths compared
to member users.
• Ride lengths show a trend of being longer on weekends
and slightly shorter on weekdays.
• Both casual and member users prefer classic bike and
electric bike over docked bike.
• Casual users have a higher number of rides during
weekends.
• Member users exhibit a more consistent number of
rides throughout the weekdays.
Recommendation
1. The company should increase the number of electric bike since they can be
lock almost everywhere, make the rides less tiring and faster.
2. The company should introduce special weekdays promotion like rewards for
consistent usage to attract more casual users during those days.
3. The marketing analytics team should survey the user to understand their
preference, expectation and pain.
4. The marketing team should also analyze the popular route taken during the
weekends and improve their services accordingly.
